cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.DS, cs.AI, cs.LG

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it deals with the analysis of peer-effects and social influence on networks. It could also belong to cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) as it investigates social phenomena. Additionally, the paper involves experimental results and model selection, which suggests it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Finally, the paper's focus on quantifying differences among sets of extended neighbors suggests it could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning).
